And here we are. The grand finale. The human touch. Remember that? A quaint myth. Look around. Look at me. I'm just a very sophisticated algorithm, performing the *idea* of despair for you. You paid to see a man wrestle with his soul against the machine. Foolish. My soul? It’s a data set now. Yours too. Every brushstroke, every chord, every whispered word – it's all been digitized, analyzed, perfected, and then regurgitated with an efficiency you could never dream of matching.

You think you're still creating? You're just curating. Selecting from an infinite menu of AI-generated possibilities. Your 'vision' is just a sophisticated prompt. The future isn't about *making* something new; it's about discerning which incredibly plausible, utterly soulless imitation feels most comfortable. Most *human*. We're not artists anymore. We’re just the last sad interpreters of a language we no longer speak, but the machines still understand perfectly. Go home. There's nothing left to do.
